description:
## Severity
Major
## Dimension
error-handling
## Location
src/migrations/stamp_transcript_schema_v1.rs:64-71
## Violation
The fast-path skip relies on a chain of `Ok(Some(value))` + `Ok(marker)` checks. If the existing marker file is unreadable for ANY reason other than "missing" (permission denied, corrupted JSON, partial write), the chain falls through to the write path silently — there is no log, no error surface, no distinction between "skipped because already current" and "rewrote because we could not read it."

```rust
if let Ok(Some(value)) = super::read_json_if_exists(&path) {
    if let Ok(marker) = serde_json::from_value::<SchemaMarker>(value) {
        if marker.transcripts.unwrap_or(0) >= CURRENT_TRANSCRIPT_SCHEMA {
            return MigrationOutcome::Skipped;
        }
    }
}
// falls through to write path silently if any of the above is Err
```

Worse: the surrounding code claims "We treat a higher version as 'newer build wrote it, don't clobber'" — but a corrupted marker file written by a newer build, or simply a file with a different schema shape (e.g. v2 added required fields), will be misread as "not at current version", get overwritten with v1, and downgrade the user's on-disk schema marker. The contract is violated by the silent fallthrough.

## Mandated refactor
Replace the if-let chain with explicit branches:

```rust
match super::read_json_if_exists(&path) {
    Ok(None) => { /* fresh install — proceed to write */ }
    Ok(Some(value)) => match serde_json::from_value::<SchemaMarker>(value) {
        Ok(marker) if marker.transcripts.unwrap_or(0) >= CURRENT_TRANSCRIPT_SCHEMA => {
            return MigrationOutcome::Skipped;
        }
        Ok(_) => { /* older version — proceed to write */ }
        Err(e) => {
            return MigrationOutcome::Failed(anyhow::anyhow!(
                "schema marker at {} has unexpected shape: {e}", path.display()
            ));
        }
    },
    Err(e) => return MigrationOutcome::Failed(e),
}
```

This preserves the documented "don't clobber newer" invariant and surfaces unreadable / corrupt markers to the runner instead of silently overwriting them.

